const a = [
  {"id":3565,"text":"Which of the following plasma proteins is involved in the transportation of free fatty acids?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 181.","responses":[{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transcobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gamma-globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3566,"text":"A 13-year-old female presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with on and off menorrhagia, bleeding gums, and petechial rashes. Her laboratory reports show the following results; Hb= 12.5 g/dl, platelet count= 350,000/mm3, activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)= 49s (normal: 29-40s). Which of the following could be the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The likely diagnosis for the 13-year-old female with on and off **menorrhagia, bleeding gums**, and **petechial rashes**, along with an **elevated activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)**, is **von Willebrand disease**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand disease is a bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of **von Willebrand factor (vWF)**, a protein involved in platelet adhesion and clot formation. The symptoms often include mucocutaneous bleeding, such as nosebleeds, easy bruising, heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding, and bleeding gums.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the normal platelet count and hemoglobin level make iron deficiency anemia less likely as a diagnosis. Anemia of chronic disease is also less likely as it typically presents with lower hemoglobin levels. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) typically presents with isolated thrombocytopenia and does not cause prolonged aPTT. Thrombotic microangiopathy usually presents with signs of microvascular thrombosis and associated organ damage, which are not described in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662.","responses":[{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"von Willebrand disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombotic microangiopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3567,"text":"An old man is brought to the emergency room in a state of unconsciousness. On examination, it is revealed that he is in a state of anaphylactic shock. Which cells in his body played a role in bringing him to this state?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 97.","responses":[{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helper T cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3568,"text":"An old woman comes to the outpatient department and is diagnosed with iron deficiency anemia. Which of the following cells will be seen on her blood smear?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Target cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bite cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Poikilocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Helmet cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3569,"text":"In sickle cell anemia, glutamate at the sixth position of the beta chain of hemoglobin is substituted by which of the following amino acids?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 635.","responses":[{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3570,"text":"Inflammation is a process regulated by several mediators. Which of the following is a negative regulator of inflammation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene B4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipoxin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemokine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostacyclin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3571,"text":"Which of these act as an opsonin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 78.","responses":[{"text":"C3a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fc portion of IgG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene B4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytokines","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3572,"text":"Which cells produce lymphokines?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 462.","responses":[{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helper T cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3573,"text":"Which of the following drugs can reverse the effects of heparin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Alkylating agents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protamine sulfate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clopidogrel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3574,"text":"A woman on warfarin therapy gets pregnant. Which drug should be administered now?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 277, 280.","responses":[{"text":"Heparin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protamine sulfate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Continue with warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3575,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for iron absorption from the intestine?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 404.","responses":[{"text":"Ceruloplasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transcobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepcidin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3576,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic of red blood cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 451.","responses":[{"text":"Biconvex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Average volume of 30 femtoliters","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"11 micrometer in diameter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Not flexible","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3577,"text":"Which of the following conditions is seen in megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 645.","responses":[{"text":"Hypersegmented eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersegmented erythrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyposegmented erythrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyposegmented neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersegmented neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3578,"text":"Where in the cell are oxygen free radicals formed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 79.","responses":[{"text":"Phagosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagolysosomes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3616,"text":"Prolonged administration of vitamin K can cause hemolytic anemia and jaundice in infants due to membrane damage of which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hemolytic anemia - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/hemolytic-anemia","responses":[{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"White blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3619,"text":"B and T cells that recognize self-antigens during their development in the lymphoid organs are destroyed at an early stage. What is this process called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 212.","responses":[{"text":"Induced tolerance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral tolerance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self tolerance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central tolerance","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3620,"text":"Which of the following is an autoimmune disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"García-Carrasco M, Pinto CM, Poblano JCS, Morales IE, Cervera R, Anaya JM. Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. El Rosario University Press; 2013. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459474/","responses":[{"text":"Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymic aplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3621,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for the tensile strength of a wound during healing?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 174","responses":[{"text":"Structural collagen modification and thinning of collagen fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrosis of wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Structural collagen modifications and collagen cross linking","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3622,"text":"A patient is given oral iron supplements. Which of the following in the diet would increase iron absorption in the gut?","explanation":null,"reference":"Lynch SR, Cook JD. Interaction of vitamin C and iron. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences. Published 1980. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6940487","responses":[{"text":"Phosphoric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetracyclines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antacids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3624,"text":"Which of the following foods cause the best iron absorption in the gut?","explanation":null,"reference":"Lynch SR, Cook JD. Interaction of vitamin C and iron. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences. Published 1980. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6940487","responses":[{"text":"Grains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Citrus fruits","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dry fruits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulses","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3625,"text":"Which of the following statement is correct regarding folic acid and vitamin B12?","explanation":"**Vitamin B12** is essential for the formation of the **active form of folic acid**.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 plays a critical role in the conversion of folic acid into its active form, known as methyltetrahydrofolate (MTHF). Without sufficient vitamin B12, folic acid cannot be properly utilized by the body. This conversion is necessary for various cellular processes, including DNA synthesis, red blood cell production, and nervous system function.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B12 alone takes part in DNA synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 plays a role in purine synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid plays a role in pyrimidine synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 is essential for the formation of the active form of folic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid is essential for the formation of the active form of vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3626,"text":"A patient comes into the outpatient department with signs and symptoms of anemia. Blood smear analysis shows microcytic anemia. Which type of microcytic anemia is associated with reduced ferritin levels?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 41-42.","responses":[{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sideroblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3628,"text":"Monocytes after entering the tissues, swell and become which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histiocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3629,"text":"Structures are said to be basophilic if they take which of the following color?","explanation":null,"reference":"Paxton S, Peckham M, Knibbs A. The leeds histology guide. Published online 2003. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.histology.leeds.ac.uk/what-is-histology/H_and_E.php","responses":[{"text":"Deep purple","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pink","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lilac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Red","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3630,"text":"Brain tumor cells are formed as a result of overexpression of a platelet-derived growth factor. A mutation in which of the following genes is responsible for this tumor formation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 284.","responses":[{"text":"Proto-oncogene","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-apoptotic gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DNA repair gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pro-apoptotic gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tumor suppressor gene","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3631,"text":"Some inflammatory mediators are cell-derived while others are plasma-derived. Which of the following groups of inflammatory mediators is plasma-derived?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 83.","responses":[{"text":"Leukotrienes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3a,C4a and C5a","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine and nitric oxide (NO)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemokines","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3633,"text":"Mesenchymal cells eventually lead to the formation of blood islands. Which of the following precursor cells play a part in this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Blood islands - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/blood-islands","responses":[{"text":"Hemoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angioblast","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Definitive heart","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3635,"text":"Which of the following is the term used to describe the time between attack by an organism and the appearance of the first symptom?","explanation":null,"reference":"van Seventer JM, Hochberg NS. Principles of infectious diseases: transmission, diagnosis, prevention, and control. International Encyclopedia of Public Health. Published online 2017:22-39. doi:10.1016/B978-0-12-803678-5.00516-6","responses":[{"text":"Incubation period","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Latent period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asymptomatic period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Easy period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infectious period","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3637,"text":"Symptoms of malaria appear due to the destruction of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 390.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3638,"text":"At what angle is the second slide held while preparing a blood smear?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"60°","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10°","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"45°","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"25°","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20°","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3639,"text":"Which of the following blood groups is devoid of both A and B agglutinogens?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 477.","responses":[{"text":"ABO","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"O","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"AB","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3640,"text":"A first-year medical student performs a blood group test in the physiology lab. He notices blood cells clumping upon the addition of anti-A and anti-B serum to the blood, however, nothing happens when anti-D serum is added. What is the blood group of the blood sample he is testing?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 479.","responses":[{"text":"O-positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A-negative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AB-positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AB-negative","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"O-negative","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3642,"text":"Interaction of warfarin with which other drug causes excessive bleeding?","explanation":null,"reference":"Crader MF, Johns T, Arnold JK. Warfarin drug interactions. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 13, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441964/","responses":[{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Protamine sulfate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3645,"text":"Which one of the following drugs is an inhibitor of ADP-induced platelet aggregation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 273.","responses":[{"text":"Clopidogrel","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tirofiban","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abciximab","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3646,"text":"Ceruloplasmin transports which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 122.","responses":[{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zinc","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3647,"text":"Chronic diseases may lead to disability and complications. This can be prevented by which level of prevention?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khasnabis C, Motsch KH, Achu K, et al. Prevention. World Health Organization; 2010. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK310943/","responses":[{"text":"Primary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Early detection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertiary prevention","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primordial prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3648,"text":"Bilirubin is conjugated with which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Bilirubin metabolism - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/bilirubin-metabolism","responses":[{"text":"Glucuronyltransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucuronic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliverdin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutathione","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3649,"text":"The sum of the squared distances of each term in the distribution from the mean, divided by the number of terms in the distribution, is called which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"El Omda S, Sergent SR. Standard deviation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 14, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574574/","responses":[{"text":"Mean","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Standard deviation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Standard error","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3650,"text":"Which of the following mediator plays no role in leukocyte recruitment to the blood vessels?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Integrins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these play a role in leukocyte recruitment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostacyclins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipoxins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3651,"text":"Which of the following types of necrosis is seen in a granulomatous infection by Mycobacterium tuberculosis?","explanation":"In a granulomatous infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the characteristic type of necrosis observed is **caseous necrosis**. Caseous necrosis is a form of coagulative necrosis characterized by the formation of a cheese-like, friable material within the affected tissue.\r\n\r\nThe term \"caseous\" refers to the gross appearance of the necrotic tissue, which resembles a soft, white, crumbly mass resembling cheese. This type of necrosis is typically seen in chronic infections, particularly those caused by certain pathogens such as Mycobacterium tuberculosis. In tuberculosis, the immune response leads to the formation of granulomas, which are aggregates of immune cells, including macrophages, surrounded by a rim of lymphocytes. The central area of the granuloma undergoes caseous necrosis, forming a central necrotic core surrounded by the granulomatous inflammation.\r\n\r\nThe presence of caseous necrosis is a hallmark feature of tuberculosis and helps in the diagnosis of the disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinoid necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gangrenous necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous granulomatous necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquefactive necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-caseating granuloma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3655,"text":"Which of the following chemical mediators cause vasodilation in acute inflammation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Vasoactive mediator - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/vasoactive-mediator","responses":[{"text":"Interleukin-1 and interleukin-6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene B4 and thromboxane A2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine and nitric oxide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C3a and C5a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemokines","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3656,"text":"Class I major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules are found on the surface of which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 194.","responses":[{"text":"B cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All nucleated cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3705,"text":"Which of the following is an example of type III immune complex hypersensitivity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 206, 207.","responses":[{"text":"Contact dermatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaphylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodpasture syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3707,"text":"Hemoglobin A1c (HbA1C) levels are used in the identification of which of the following diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1106.","responses":[{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sideroblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3708,"text":"Erythropoietin is a hormone that promotes hematopoiesis. Which of the following organ is responsible for its production?","explanation":null,"reference":"Donnelly S. Why is erythropoietin made in the kidney? The kidney functions as a critmeter. American Journal of Kidney Diseases: The Official Journal of the National Kidney Foundation. Published August 2001. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11479173/","responses":[{"text":"Gall bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3709,"text":"What is the process of production of the solid components of blood called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Munker R, Munker R, Hiller E, Glass J, Paquette R. Basic biology of hemopoiesis. Modern Hematology: Biology and Clinical Management. https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-59745-149-9_1","responses":[{"text":"Hemopoiesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphopoiesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombopoiesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukopoiesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythropoiesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3711,"text":"Which of the following conditions would give rise to hypersegmented leukocytes seen on microscopic examination?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 45.","responses":[{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sideroblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3712,"text":"Lobed nucleus, bluish-purple cytoplasmic granules, and release of histamine are characteristics of which of the following white blood cell?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3713,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect about central tolerance?","explanation":null,"reference":"Immunological tolerance - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/immunological-tolerance","responses":[{"text":"Ensures that mature T-cells don't recognize self-antigens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self-antigens can be expressed on thymus epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lack of central tolerance can result in autoimmune disorders","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central tolerance occurs only in thymus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immature T-cell recognizes self antigens and undergo apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3714,"text":"Which of the following is the best diagnostic test for thalassemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Brancaleoni V, Di Pierro E, Motta I, Cappellini MD. Laboratory diagnosis of thalassemia. International Journal of Laboratory Hematology. Published May 2016. Accessed June 13, 2022. https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/ijlh.12527","responses":[{"text":"Peripheral blood smear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red cell distribution Width (RDW)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin electrophoresis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymerase chain reaction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3715,"text":"What is the composition of hemoglobin A or HbA1?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 27.","responses":[{"text":"4  beta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 alpha and 3 beta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 alpha and 1 beta chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 delta and 2 beta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha and 2 beta chains","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3716,"text":"Which cells are involved in hypersensitivity type 1?","explanation":null,"reference":"Abbas M, Moussa M, Akel H. Type i hypersensitivity reaction. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 13, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560561/","responses":[{"text":"Mast cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3717,"text":"What antibodies are involved in hypersensitivity type 1?","explanation":null,"reference":"Abbas M, Moussa M, Akel H. Type i hypersensitivity reaction. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 13, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560561/","responses":[{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3718,"text":"Which of the following cells are involved in the formation of epithelioid cells and giant cells in granulomatous inflammation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 97.","responses":[{"text":"B cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3721,"text":"Which of the following is a common mixed tumor of the oral cavity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 100.","responses":[{"text":"Mucosal melanoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubular adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleomorphic adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3722,"text":"Which of the following is the most common oral cancer?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dhanuthai K, Rojanawatsirivej S, Thosaporn W, et al. Oral cancer: A multicenter study. Med Oral Patol Oral Cir Bucal. 2018;23(1):e23-e29. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5822535/","responses":[{"text":"Papillary adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Melanoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematologic tumors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3723,"text":"Which of the following best describes carcinoma in situ?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 271.","responses":[{"text":"Dysplasia of epithelium without the invasion of basement membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysplasia of epithelium with the invasion of basement membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma in 1/3rd epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysplasia of epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma in 2/3rd epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3725,"text":"By what means do white blood cells move through tissue spaces?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 457.","responses":[{"text":"Floating","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extravasation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoeboid movement","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3726,"text":"What is the amount of hemoglobin in a 70 kg man?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"900 g","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"700 g","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"500 g","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 g","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1200 g","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3727,"text":"A woman presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with bleeding gums, epistaxis, and non-palpable rashes. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kirchmaier CM, Pillitteri D. Diagnosis and management of inherited platelet disorders. Transfusion Medicine and Hemotherapy. Published October 2010. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2980508/","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet disorder","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3728,"text":"Which of the following is the most common oral cancer-causing agent?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 416-417.","responses":[{"text":"Tobacco","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Benzene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestos","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3729,"text":"Which of the following research method is used to describe and evaluate different aspects of a disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"6. 5 observational research – research methods in psychology. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://opentext.wsu.edu/carriecuttler/chapter/observational-research/","responses":[{"text":"Hypothetical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Numerical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Descriptive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Observational","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3731,"text":"Which of the following is a chromoprotein?","explanation":null,"reference":"\"Chromoprotein - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/chromoprotein\"","responses":[{"text":"Actin and myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immunoglobulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3732,"text":"A child with a bone marrow disorder is undergoing a blood transfusion. He has also been given 400 ml citrate intravenously to prevent blood clotting. After three transfusions, which of the following conditions will be observed in the child’s blood?","explanation":null,"reference":"Li K, Xu Y. Citrate metabolism in blood transfusions and its relationship due to metabolic alkalosis and respiratory acidosis. Int J Clin Exp Med. 2015;8(4):6578-6584. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4483798/","responses":[{"text":"Hypocalcemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypercalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3733,"text":"In which of the following disease the rate of synthesis of the globin chains is defective?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 43.","responses":[{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobinopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3734,"text":"Immunoglobulins are produced by which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 469.","responses":[{"text":"B cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3735,"text":"In which of the following disorder, antibodies are produced against the body's own immunoglobulin G (IgG)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1209-1210.","responses":[{"text":"DiGeorge syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaphylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3736,"text":"Which isotype of antibodies is found on immature B-cells?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3738,"text":"Which of the following statements is true regarding immunoglobulins?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 469.","responses":[{"text":"They are formed by helper T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are formed by cytotoxic T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are formed by B-cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"They are all monoclonal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are formed by thymus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3739,"text":"In porphyrias, which of the following factors is involved?","explanation":null,"reference":"Heme synthesis - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/heme-synthesis","responses":[{"text":"An excess of inhibitors of heme synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced enzymes of heme synthesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"An excess of haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced intermediates of heme synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3740,"text":"Interleukin-5 (IL-5) is required for the activation of which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3741,"text":"Where is the mean found in a positively skewed data distribution?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Extreme left of the distribution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extreme top of the distribution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extreme right of the distribution","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Between mean and mode","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bottom of the distribution","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3742,"text":"A histologist is studying a blood smear under a microscope. He observes an anucleated, biconcave, disc-shaped cell. Which of the following cells has he observed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 7th ed. Paramount; 2021: 75.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3743,"text":"Which of these is the correct composition of hemoglobin Gower 1?","explanation":null,"reference":"Embryonic hemoglobin - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/embryonic-hemoglobin","responses":[{"text":"2 alpha and 2 delta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 zeta and 2 epsilon chains","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha and 2 epsilon chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha and 2 beta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 alpha and 2 gamma chains","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3744,"text":"How long after birth does the transition from HbF to HbA take place in patients with thalassemia major?","explanation":null,"reference":"Herbert L. Muncie J, Campbell JS. Alpha and beta thalassemia. afp. 2009;80(4):339-344. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2009/0815/p339.html","responses":[{"text":"1 year","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1-2 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6-9 months","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3745,"text":"In sickle cell anemia, which type of hemoglobin is most useful?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 47.","responses":[{"text":"HbA1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbF","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbC","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3770,"text":"Which system reaches the functional state first in the embryo?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 63.","responses":[{"text":"Nervous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excretory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiovascular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skeletal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3772,"text":"Where are white infarcts usually seen?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Testes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Small intestine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3774,"text":"Where does red infarct usually occur in?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 131.","responses":[{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial occlusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Venous occlusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3779,"text":"A patient with liver cirrhosis comes with abdominal distention (ascites). Ascites is due to the low level of protein in the plasma. Which of the following proteins could be low?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 829.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gamma globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microglobulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3801,"text":"Which of the following is the characteristic of a benign tumor?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 270.","responses":[{"text":"Metaplastic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Poorly differentiated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Well differentiated","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaplastic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Invasive","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3802,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic of malignant tumors?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 274.","responses":[{"text":"Atrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaplasia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3806,"text":"Through which process do reticulocytes enter peripheral blood circulation from bone marrow?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Pinocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3818,"text":"What does a bacteriostatic agent do?","explanation":null,"reference":"Loree J, Lappin SL. Bacteriostatic antibiotics. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 30, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547678/","responses":[{"text":"Increases growth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slows viral growth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maintains human cell growth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits the growth of bacteria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3845,"text":"Hemolytic disease of newborn due to Rh incompatibility is caused by which type of hypersensitivity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 205.","responses":[{"text":"Complement mediated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contact type","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune complex mediated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaphylactic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3848,"text":"Which of the following is a unique stain used in histological studies?","explanation":null,"reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 73,74,75.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophilia (pink stain) for neutrophil granules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia (red stain) for hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Azurophilia (purple stain) for lysosome of WBCs","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilia (yellow stain) for hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilia (blue stain) for DNA in ribosomes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3912,"text":"What is the inheritance pattern of sickle cell anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 47.","responses":[{"text":"X-linked dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked recessive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondrial","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3913,"text":"Classic hemophilia is caused by the deficiency of which of the following factors/parts of factors?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Small part of factor VIII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small part of factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large part of factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large part of factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3914,"text":"What is the most common cause of iron loss?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 651.","responses":[{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic blood loss","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cell turnover","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiological demands","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3917,"text":"Which of the following would be the most useful to test iron deficiency anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 42.","responses":[{"text":"Iron profile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Homocysteine levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3919,"text":"Which of the following is correct about the rate of multiplication of bacteria in the log phase?","explanation":null,"reference":"9: Microbial growth. Biology LibreTexts. Published February 6, 2018. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://bio.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Microbiology/Book%3A_Microbiology_(Bruslind)/09%3A_Microbial_Growth","responses":[{"text":"It depends on the environment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is decreasing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is constant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is increasing","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is zero","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3920,"text":"Hemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN) can be categorized as which type of hypersensitivity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 205.","responses":[{"text":"Type 5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3924,"text":"Which of the following is the causative agent of syphilis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 378.","responses":[{"text":"Mycobacterium pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treponema pallidum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3962,"text":"The female Anopheles mosquito is responsible for the transmission of which of the following diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 390.","responses":[{"text":"Syphilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elephantiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"AIDS( Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3964,"text":"Conjugated bilirubin after entering into the intestine is modified by the action of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 885.","responses":[{"text":"Fecal matter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gut bacteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3967,"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is a part of the normal flora of which of the following regions?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Nasopharynx","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3993,"text":"Which option correctly describes the appearance of red blood cells in aplastic anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 654.","responses":[{"text":"Macrocytic hyperchromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic normochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic hyperchromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic normochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrocytic normochromic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3994,"text":"What is the site of erythropoiesis after seven months of in-utero life?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Yellow marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red marrow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3995,"text":"Which of the following substances is a plasminogen activator inhibitor?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 290.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fresh frozen plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminocaproic acid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3996,"text":"Which of the following statements is incorrect regarding lymph nodes?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Paracortex of nodes contains T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hassall's corpuscles are present in the medulla of lymph nodes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphatic sinuses are present in nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They have high vascular endothelial venules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortex has germinal centers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3997,"text":"Cell-mediated immunity is related to which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 197-198.","responses":[{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4000,"text":"By decreasing the levels of which of the following substances does aspirin inhibit platelet aggregation?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"COX-1 (cyclooxygenase-1)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipoxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4003,"text":"Which of the following is a direct plasminogen activator?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 288.","responses":[{"text":"Urokinase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alteplase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenecteplase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reteplase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptokinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4005,"text":"Which protein is abundantly present in neoplastic cells?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Telomerase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytochrome C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4006,"text":"Which clotting factors are activated by vitamin K?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 661.","responses":[{"text":"III, IV, V, and X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"III, V, VII, and IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"II, V, VI, and IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"II, VII, IX, and X","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"II, VI, VII, and IX","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4009,"text":"Which of the following options represents the correct characteristics of red blood cells in the blood smears of a patient suffering from thalassemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 640.","responses":[{"text":"Nucleated cells, target cells, and microcytic, normochromic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleated cells, target cells, and microcytic, hypochromic cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-nucleated cells, target cells, and microcytic, hypochromic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-nucleated cells and normocytic, hypochromic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleated cells, target cells, and microcytic, hyperchromic cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4012,"text":"Which of the following is not an anti-platelet drug?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 288-289.","responses":[{"text":"Urokinase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ticlopidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prasugrel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clopidogrel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dipyridamole","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4014,"text":"A 5-year-old boy comes to the outpatient department complaining of a painful and swollen knee. On examination, bleeding is seen within the knee joint but with no signs of physical trauma. His mother gives a family history of a maternal uncle who recently died of a bleeding disorder. Investigations show isolated increased APTT. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hemophilia A** is an X-linked recessive disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of coagulation factor VIII.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of a painful and swollen joint without a history of physical trauma suggests an intra-articular hemorrhage. Hemophilia A leads to impaired blood clotting, specifically due to a deficiency of factor VIII, which is involved in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation. As a result, patients with hemophilia A are prone to prolonged APTT (activated partial thromboplastin time).\r\n\r\nThe X-linked inheritance pattern explains the family history of a maternal uncle with a bleeding disorder. Hemophilia A predominantly affects males, while females are usually carriers of the disease.\r\n\r\nConfirmatory laboratory tests may include specific assays to measure factor VIII activity or genetic testing to identify mutations in the factor VIII gene.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662-663.","responses":[{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic uremic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4019,"text":"The presence of pus and swelling in the tonsils indicates which of the following conditions?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophilia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4021,"text":"Porphyria results in the accumulation of a unique pattern of intermediates caused by the deficiency of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Gounden V, Jialal I. Acute porphyria. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 3, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537352/","responses":[{"text":"Heme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzyme","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermediate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4032,"text":"A cell can divide a maximum of up to 30-35 times, however, neoplastic cells do not have a limited number of cell divisions. This characteristic of neoplastic cells can be attributed to which of the following factors?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Mutation in DNA repair gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upregulated telomerase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"P53 mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclin gene mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Over-expression of growth factor receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4037,"text":"Which of the following conditions is associated with the complications of heparin intake?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomalacia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4039,"text":"Where does erythropoiesis occur from birth till the age of 5?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Yellow marrow of long bones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only in the sternum and hip bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only in the vertebrae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only in long bones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red marrow of long bones","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4041,"text":"A 16-year-old girl comes to the clinic with complaints of recurrent infections and itching. She has a family history of the same problem. The diagnosis relates to a deficiency in innate response. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 237.","responses":[{"text":"Leukocyte adhesion deficiency (LAD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Common variable immunodeficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DiGeorge syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe combined immunodeficiency disorder (SCID)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked lymphoproliferative syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4045,"text":"Innate immunity is considered to be the first line of defense against many microorganisms. Its major component includes which of the following?","explanation":"Innate immunity is the first line of defense against pathogens and plays a crucial role in protecting the body from infection. One of its major components is the **skin**.\r\n\r\nThe skin acts as a physical barrier that prevents the entry of microorganisms and foreign substances into the body. It consists of multiple layers of epithelial cells that are tightly packed together, making it difficult for pathogens to penetrate. Additionally, the skin produces antimicrobial substances such as defensins and cathelicidins, which have antimicrobial properties and help in destroying invading microorganisms.\r\n\r\nInnate immunity also includes other components such as **mucous membranes**, which line the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and genitourinary tracts and secrete mucus that traps and removes pathogens. **Phagocytes** (such as neutrophils and macrophages) are another important component of innate immunity, as they engulf and destroy pathogens through phagocytosis.\r\n\r\nWhile B-cells, T-cells, and antibodies are part of the adaptive immune response, the skin is a critical component of the innate immune system, providing a physical barrier and other defense mechanisms against pathogens.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 459.","responses":[{"text":"Plasma cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4047,"text":"A girl comes to the outpatient department with complaints of epistaxis and small bruising on her skin. While giving her history she informs the physician that her sister has the same problem. Laboratory analysis shows that her partial thromboplastin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) are normal but prolonged bleeding time. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Bernard-Soulier syndrome (BSS)** is a rare inherited bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of the glycoprotein complex **GPIb-IX-V** on platelets.\r\n\r\nThe clinical features of BSS include mucocutaneous bleeding, such as epistaxis (nosebleeds), easy bruising, and prolonged bleeding after minor injuries. Laboratory analysis typically reveals normal **partial thromboplastin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)**, which indicates the normal function of the intrinsic and common coagulation pathways. However, the **bleeding time** is prolonged due to impaired platelet adhesion and aggregation.\r\n\r\nThe underlying defect in BSS lies in the deficiency or dysfunction of the GPIb-IX-V complex, which plays a crucial role in mediating platelet adhesion to von Willebrand factor (vWF) on damaged blood vessel walls. Without proper platelet adhesion, hemostasis is compromised, leading to a tendency for bleeding.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that Hemophilia A and Hemophilia B are characterized by deficiencies of clotting factors VIII and IX, respectively, which would manifest as abnormal PT and aPTT results.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 117, 119, 660.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 433-434.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bernard-Soulier syndrome (BSS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4052,"text":"A 15-year-old boy comes to the outpatient department with a prolonged history of hemarthrosis (bleeding and swelling into muscles and joints) and unexplained bleeding from small bruises. Laboratory examination shows prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) as well as prolonged bleeding time. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand disease (vWD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4055,"text":"Raynaud's phenomenon and fibrosis of GI tract, skin, and tissues are symptoms of which of the following?","explanation":"**Systemic sclerosis** is a chronic autoimmune connective tissue disorder characterized by excessive fibrosis and vascular abnormalities. It primarily affects the skin, but it can also involve various organs such as the GI tract, lungs, kidneys, and heart.\r\n\r\nRaynaud's phenomenon, characterized by episodic vasospasm of the digital arteries in response to cold or stress, is a common early manifestation of systemic sclerosis. Fibrosis of the GI tract can lead to symptoms such as difficulty swallowing, acid reflux, and impaired absorption of nutrients.\r\n\r\nThe exact cause of systemic sclerosis is unknown, but it involves dysregulation of the immune system and activation of fibroblasts, leading to excessive production of collagen and deposition of extracellular matrix components.\r\n\r\nPolymyositis is an inflammatory muscle disease, DiGeorge syndrome is a congenital immunodeficiency disorder, multiple sclerosis is a demyelinating disease of the central nervous system, and Marfan's syndrome is a genetic disorder affecting connective tissue. None of these conditions exhibit the specific symptoms described in the question.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 228.","responses":[{"text":"DiGeorge syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic sclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymyositis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4058,"text":"A 5-year-old boy is brought to the clinic with the complaint of a swelling in the neck. On examination, his cervical lymph nodes are hard, tough, and immobile. What is the most likely diagnosis on the basis of examination?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutropenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hodgkin's lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4064,"text":"Which infection is caused by plasmodium falciparum?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Sleeping sickness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascariasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chagas disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Babesiosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4065,"text":"The special propensity to collect in tissues undergoing allergic reactions is demonstrated by which of the following types of WBCs?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 96, 97.","responses":[{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4066,"text":"Which of the following is true about a trophozoite?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"It is the non-motile stage of a lifecycle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the feeding and reproducing stage of a lifecycle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the infectious stage of a lifecycle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the death stage of a lifecycle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the vector stage of a lifecycle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4291,"text":"What is the daily requirement for Vitamin B12?","explanation":null,"reference":"Folate I of M (US) SC on the SE of DRI and its P on, Vitamins OB, Choline A. Vitamin b12. Published 1998. Accessed May 30, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK114302/","responses":[{"text":"80-100 μg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10-15 μg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2-3 μg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"30-35 μg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.05-1 μg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4309,"text":"Which of the following is the function of tumor necrosis factor (TNF) in septic shock?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophil diapedesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Detachment of cells from endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotaxis of white blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4310,"text":"Which of the following is an appropriate diagnostic method for a Leishmania infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 392.","responses":[{"text":"Intestinal cross section","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral blood film","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count(CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cross section","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4311,"text":"Sudden ischemia resulting from vascular occlusion leads to which of the following types of necrosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 5.","responses":[{"text":"Coagulative necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinoid necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4312,"text":"The brain undergoes which of the following types of necrosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 5.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinoid necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquefactive necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulative necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4322,"text":"Which of the following factors contributes to infarction in an organ?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 5.","responses":[{"text":"Carbondioxide concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occlusion of the lymphatic supply of an organ","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon monoxide concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Edema in the organ","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occlusion of the vascular supply of an organ","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4323,"text":"Infarction results in which of the following types of necrosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 131.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinoid necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquefactive necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4328,"text":"Intrinsic factor is synthesized by which of the following cells?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Chief cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucoid cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4329,"text":"Which of the following vitamins is related to the metabolism of folic acid?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"B6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B12","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4331,"text":"Iron deficiency affects which of the following mechanisms?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Homocysteine synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylmalonic acid synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin synthesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4333,"text":"Iron absorption occurs in which part of the gut?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 650.","responses":[{"text":"Ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal duodenum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4334,"text":"A 24-year-old male presents in the outpatient department with headache, tremors, and mood changes. The patient also gives a history of fly bite. The posterior cervical lymph nodes are also enlarged. Which protozoan parasite might be the cause?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Plasmodium falciparum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leishmania donovani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumocystis jirovecii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trypanosoma gambiense","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxoplasma gondii","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4356,"text":"Which stage of P. falciparum is crescent shaped?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"Ring stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gametocyte stage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oocyte stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporoite stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schizont stage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4372,"text":"Which of the following statements regarding the role of retinoblastoma (Rb) gene during the cell cycle is correct?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 26.","responses":[{"text":"It promotes the transition from G2 to M phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It inhibits the transition from G2 to M phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It promotes the transition from G1 to S phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It inhibits the transition from G1 to S phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It promotes the transition from M to G₀ phase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4385,"text":"A 24-year-old male presents in the outpatient department with headache, tremors, and mood changes. The patient also gives a history of fly bite. The posterior cervical lymph nodes are also enlarged. Which of the following conditions can this be?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Black sickness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sleeping sickness","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracranial calcification","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megacolon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4387,"text":"Which of the following organism acts as an insect vector for Trypanosoma gambiense?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Diptera","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tsetse fly","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sand fly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anopheles mosquito","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deer fly","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4388,"text":"Which of the following tests is most commonly used to detect infection with Trypanosoma gambiense in the early stages of the disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"CDC - African trypanosomiasis - diagnosis. Published April 28, 2020. Accessed June 16, 2022. https://www.cdc.gov/parasites/sleepingsickness/diagnosis.html","responses":[{"text":"Screening tests for antibody detection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood smears revealing trypomastigotes in blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Culture of organism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4389,"text":"Which of the following drugs is usually used for the treatment of sleeping sickness?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Atovaquone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benzimidazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ibuprofen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sumarin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium stibogluconate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4390,"text":"How much erythropoietin is produced by kidneys?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 442.","responses":[{"text":"80%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"65%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"70%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"90%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"95%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4391,"text":"Which of the following can be the most reliable indicator that can be used to differentiate between benign and malignant tumors?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 271.","responses":[{"text":"Invasion of local tissues","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytoplasmic eosinophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Degree of hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nuclear basophilia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4393,"text":"Which of the following is the mechanical factor that plays its role in the sterility of the genitourinary tract?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"B cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary flow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4400,"text":"Which malarial parasite causes severe malaria?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 390-391.","responses":[{"text":"Plasmodium malariae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium vivax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium knowlesi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium ovale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium falciparum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4404,"text":"Pernicious anemia can result from which of the following conditions?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Esophagitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrectomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4407,"text":"Which of the following is the optimum temperature for growth of bacteria?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"120 °C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4 °C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"37 °C","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"100 °C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"50 °C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4414,"text":"Which of the following is the best test for the diagnosis of malaria?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 391.","responses":[{"text":"Enzyme-linked immunoassay (ELISA) test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick and thin film","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pap smear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microbiological culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serologic test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4415,"text":"Which of the following can play its role as an anticoagulant to prevent further clotting around the injured part after a clot has been formed there?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Factor XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4418,"text":"Which of the following is not a sign of acute inflammation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 71.","responses":[{"text":"Warmth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Redness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4420,"text":"Which of the following cells are seen abundantly in the blood of a person infected by a helminth?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4423,"text":"In extremely rare diseases, the calculated odds are equal to which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Rate ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevalence ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Difference ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relative risk/risk ratio","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Odds ratio","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4424,"text":"Which of the following leads to infarction in a tissue?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Ischemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High blood supply","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Necroptosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4425,"text":"Most of the iron in the storage pool is in the form of which of the following?","explanation":"The majority of iron in the storage pool is in the form of **ferritin**. Ferritin is an intracellular protein complex that serves as an iron storage molecule. It is found in cells, particularly in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow. Ferritin stores iron in a non-toxic and readily available form.\r\n\r\nWhen iron levels are high, excess iron is bound to ferritin and stored within cells. As iron demand increases, ferritin releases iron to meet the body's needs. This allows for a regulated release of iron into the bloodstream for transportation to sites of utilization.\r\n\r\nHemosiderin, another iron storage complex, is derived from ferritin. It is an insoluble and aggregated form of ferritin that accumulates in cells during periods of iron overload or when there is an imbalance in iron metabolism.\r\n\r\nTransferrin is a transport protein that binds to iron in the bloodstream and delivers it to cells. Apotransferrin refers to transferrin without bound iron.\r\n\r\nWhile some iron may exist as free ions, the majority is bound to ferritin within the storage pool.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 874.","responses":[{"text":"Apotransferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Free iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4426,"text":"Which diagnostic test is done for megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 645.","responses":[{"text":"Homocysteine levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylmalonic acid levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum folic acid and B12","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4428,"text":"Which of the following drugs does not affect wound healing?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetracycline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4430,"text":"\"Since when has the disease been occurring?\", \"Where is it occurring?\", \"What is the type of person getting the disease?\". What type of diagnosis is being done by asking questions like these?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Descriptive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Analytical","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4434,"text":"A 10-year-old male comes to the emergency room with burns. His complete blood count (CBC) shows neutrophilia with 40 x 10⁹/L WBCs. What reaction causes this neutrophilia?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Chronic inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug reaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthus reaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4437,"text":"What is the first step for an outbreak investigation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Fricker RD, Rigdon SE. Investigating a disease outbreak. Significance (Oxford, England). Published April 2020. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7169535/","responses":[{"text":"Verification of diagnosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesize","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case definition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Communicating findings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Test hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4445,"text":"Which of the following is not associated with a patient suffering from a disease caused by Trypanosoma cruzi?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Palpable swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chagoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatosplenomegaly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sleeping sickness","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4460,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding the normal flora in humans?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Formed after the neonatal period","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Not present in the stomach at all due to an acidic pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Not affected by antimicrobial drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The same numbers and types of organisms inhabit the throat and the bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formed in intra-uterine life","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4464,"text":"A 5-year-old boy was diagnosed with chronic granulomatous disease (CGD). CGD is a disease associated with a defect in the oxidative burst. Which of the following cells are affected in CGD?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 238.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural killer cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4466,"text":"A blister is an example of which type of inflammation?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Purulent inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinoid inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4470,"text":"What does heparin activate?","explanation":"**Heparin** activates **antithrombin III (AT III)**. Heparin binds to AT III and enhances its ability to inactivate several coagulation factors, including thrombin (Factor IIa) and Factors IXa, Xa, XIa, and XIIa. By accelerating the inhibitory action of AT III, heparin helps to regulate and inhibit the clotting process.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 285-286.","responses":[{"text":"Thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4480,"text":"What is the inheritance pattern of thalassemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Thalassemia - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/thalassemia","responses":[{"text":"X-linked dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Y-linked","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked recessive","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4502,"text":"What enzyme catalyzes the first step of heme degradation?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Protoporphyrinogen  oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta aminolevulinic acid synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heme oxygenase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliverdin reductase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heme reductase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4507,"text":"Which type of antibody plays a dominant role in helminth infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015.","responses":[{"text":"Ig M","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ig D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ig G","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ig A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ig E","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4511,"text":"Which type of hemoglobin plays a protective role in infants against thalassemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 44.","responses":[{"text":"HbF","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbC","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4513,"text":"In a fetus aged 2-7 months, what is the main site of hemopoiesis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Yolk sac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Red marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4517,"text":"What is the typical blood picture in thalassemia?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Intrinsic hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrocytic, megaloblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Target cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic, hypochromic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bite cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4519,"text":"What does non-tender and rubbery submandibular, cervical, and axillary lymphadenopathy indicate?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 588.","responses":[{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Melanoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4543,"text":"The main contributor to the production of erythropoietin is the kidney. Which of the following is another organ that is also involved in the production of erythropoietin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 442.","responses":[{"text":"Long bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10113,"text":"Which of the following is the first clotting factor that is common in both extrinsic and intrinsic pathway?","explanation":"The first clotting factor that is common to both the extrinsic and intrinsic pathways of coagulation is **Factor X**, also known as Stuart-Prower factor. Factor X is an important enzyme that plays a key role in the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin, which is a critical step in the clotting process.\r\n\r\nThe extrinsic pathway is initiated by the release of tissue factor (Factor III) from damaged endothelial cells or extravascular tissues. Tissue factor combines with Factor VII to form an activated complex that activates Factor X. On the other hand, the intrinsic pathway is triggered by activation of Factor XII by contact with exposed subendothelial components. The activated Factor XII then leads to the sequential activation of other factors, including Factor XI, Factor IX, and Factor VIII, ultimately leading to the activation of Factor X.\r\n\r\nOnce Factor X is activated, it converges with the common pathway of coagulation, leading to the formation of a fibrin clot.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 487-488.","responses":[{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11773,"text":"Which of the following terms refers to the constant presence of a disease or infectious agent within a given geographical area or population group?","explanation":"The term that refers to the **constant presence** of a disease or infectious agent within a given geographical area or population group is **endemic**. Endemic diseases are those that are habitually present at a **baseline level** within a specific region or population.\r\n\r\nIn an endemic situation, the disease or infectious agent is consistently present and maintained within the population without the need for external introductions. The prevalence of the disease remains relatively stable over time within the defined area or population.\r\n\r\nSporadic refers to the occurrence of isolated cases of a disease that are scattered or irregularly distributed in terms of time and place.\r\n\r\nExotic refers to diseases that are not native to a particular region or population and are introduced from outside.\r\n\r\nPandemic refers to the worldwide spread of a new disease, affecting large populations across multiple countries or continents.\r\n\r\nEpidemic refers to a sudden increase in the number of cases of a disease above the expected level in a specific population or geographical area.","reference":"Principles of epidemiology: glossary. Published December 20, 2021. Accessed June 14, 2022. https://www.cdc.gov/csels/dsepd/ss1978/glossary.html","responses":[{"text":"Endemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a